Today, at my linear algebra exam, there was this question that I couldn't solve. Prove that $$\det \begin{bmatrix} 
n^{2} & (n+1)^{2} &(n+2)^{2} \\ 
(n+1)^{2} &(n+2)^{2}  & (n+3)^{2}\\ 
(n+2)^{2} & (n+3)^{2} & (n+4)^{2}
\end{bmatrix} = -8$$ Clearly, calculating the determinant, with the matrix as it is, wasn't the right way. The calculations went on and on. But I couldn't think of any other way to solve it. Is there any way to simplify $A$ , so as to calculate the determinant?

LEt $f$ be given as $$
f(x,y) =
\begin{cases}
\frac{ \sin x - \sin y }{x-y}, & \text{if }\text{ $x \neq y $} \\
\cos x, & \text{if } x \text{ $=y$}
\end{cases}
$$ Notice when $y=x$, along the diagonal, $f = \cos x$ which is continuous everywhere. if $y \neq x$, then $f(x,y) = \frac{ \sin x - \sin y}{x-y}$, which I claim is continuous also everywhere. To show this, let $\epsilon > 0$ be given. and take $(x,y), (u,v) \in \mathbb{R}^2 \setminus \{ (t,t) \} $. We want to estimate $$ \left| \frac{ \sin x - \sin y }{x-y} - \frac{ \sin u - \sin v }{u-v} \right|$$ given that $||(x,y) - (u,v)|| = \sqrt{ (x-u)^2 + (y-v)^2} < \delta $ for some $\delta > 0 $. How can I estimate so that we can choose an appropiate $\delta$ ?
